## Section 3: Island Biogeography Theory — MacArthur and Wilson (1967)

This is one of the most tested theoretical frameworks in all of ecology and biogeography. Almost every JRF paper has at least one question touching this.

### The Core Question

Why do larger islands have more species than smaller islands? Why do islands closer to the mainland have more species than remote ones? Robert MacArthur and E.O. Wilson answered this with mathematical elegance in their 1967 book "The Theory of Island Biogeography."

### The Two Processes

Every island has two processes happening simultaneously:

**Immigration (colonisation):** New species arrive from the mainland. The rate of immigration depends on two things — the distance from the mainland (farther = lower immigration rate, because fewer individuals make the crossing) and the number of species already on the island (the more species present, the fewer new species can arrive because most arriving individuals belong to species already there).

**Extinction:** Species already on the island go extinct. The rate of extinction depends on two things — the size of the island (smaller = higher extinction rate, because populations are smaller and more vulnerable) and the number of species on the island (more species = higher extinction rate because of competition and predation).

### The Equilibrium

When the immigration rate equals the extinction rate, the island reaches an **equilibrium species number (Ŝ)**. This is not a fixed set of species — species come and go — but the total number remains roughly constant. This is called **species turnover**.

### The Species-Area Relationship

The mathematical expression of this is:

**S = cA^z**

Where S = number of species, A = area of the island, c = a constant (varies by taxon and region), z = a constant (typically 0.20–0.35 for true islands; ~0.12–0.17 for habitat patches on continents).

In log form: **log S = log c + z log A**

This means that if you increase the area of a habitat by 10 times, you approximately **double** the number of species (when z ≈ 0.3).

The practical conservation implication: when you fragment a large forest into small patches, you are effectively creating "islands" in a sea of agriculture or urban land. Each patch will lose species until it reaches the new (lower) equilibrium for its smaller area. This is the theoretical basis for why **habitat fragmentation** is so destructive, and why large contiguous protected areas are far better than many small ones.### Rescue Effect

If an island has very low extinction — because immigrants from the mainland keep "rescuing" declining populations with new individuals — this is called the **rescue effect**. It means near islands have lower effective extinction rates than the simple model predicts.

### SLOSS Debate — Single Large Or Several Small

One of the most practical debates in conservation biology, directly derived from island biogeography theory. If you have a fixed total area to protect, is it better to have one single large reserve, or several small reserves of the same total area?

Arguments for Single Large (SL): One large reserve can support a complete ecosystem including apex predators that need huge territories (tigers, elephants). It has less edge effect. It supports larger populations with less inbreeding risk. Island biogeography predicts fewer extinctions.

Arguments for Several Small (SS): Several small reserves protect more different locations and habitats. If one is destroyed by disease or fire, others survive. They can be scattered across different biogeographic zones capturing more diversity.

The current consensus: for most taxa, **a single large reserve is better** — but a network of well-connected reserves linked by corridors (creating a "metapopulation" landscape) is the ideal. This connects to corridor ecology and landscape ecology.

