## Section 5: Endemism — The Core Measure of Biogeographic Uniqueness

### Types of Endemism

**Palaeoendemics (Relict endemics):** Species that were once widespread but are now restricted to one region because their former range has been eliminated by climate change or habitat destruction. Example: Dawn redwood (Metasequoia) — once found across the Northern Hemisphere in the fossil record, now endemic to a small area in China.

**Neoendemics:** Recently evolved species that haven't had time to spread beyond their origin point. Example: Darwin's finches — each Galápagos island has its own finch species, all recently evolved from a common ancestor. Lake Victoria cichlid fishes — hundreds of species evolved within the last 15,000 years.

**Microendemics:** Species restricted to an incredibly tiny area — a single mountain, lake, or island. Example: Namdapha flying squirrel (Biswamoyopterus biswasi) — known only from a single specimen from Namdapha National Park in Arunachal Pradesh. Critically endangered by definition.

### Why High Endemism Matters for Conservation

A species that is endemic is irreplaceable. If its entire habitat is destroyed, it goes globally extinct — there is no other population to recolonise from. This is why endemic species are weighted so heavily in conservation priority-setting. The loss of an endemic is the loss of a unique evolutionary lineage — millions of years of evolution, gone forever.

