## Section 7: The Great American Biotic Interchange — A Case Study in Realms Connecting

This is a perfect example of what happens when two previously isolated biogeographic realms suddenly connect — and it's a JRF favourite because it illustrates so many principles at once.

About **3 million years ago**, the Isthmus of Panama formed, connecting North and South America for the first time in ~30 million years. What happened next was the **Great American Biotic Interchange (GABI)**:

Species moved both ways — but the exchange was highly asymmetric. North American species (large carnivores: ancestors of jaguars, pumas, bears; large herbivores: tapirs, deer, horses, mastodons) invaded South America. South American species (ground sloths, glyptodonts, armadillos, opossums, capybaras) invaded North America.

The outcome was also asymmetric: **North American invaders largely replaced South American natives in ecological dominance.** Why? North America had been connected to Eurasia via Bering — so its fauna had been competing and evolving in a larger, more competitive "evolutionary arena" (this is called **escalation** in evolution). South American fauna had evolved in isolation and was less competitive. Today, most of South America's large mammal fauna is derived from North American immigrants (jaguar, tapir, deer, peccary), while only a few South American lineages (armadillos, opossums, ground sloths — though the latter went extinct) made it north successfully.

The lesson: **biogeographic isolation produces unique fauna, but also potentially less competitive fauna.** This has direct parallels to what happens when invasive species from competitive ecosystems enter isolated island systems today — the invasives typically win.

